Problem Description
Coding Hands-on > 1: Easy : Dual Conveyor Merge
A factory has two conveyor belts, A and B, feeding items to a single packing station.
Belt A carries N items with values a[0], a[1], ..., a[N-1], and Belt B carries M items with values b[0], b[1], ..., b[M-1]. Items on each belt are queued: you can only take the front item from a belt (i.e., a[0] must be taken before a[1], and b[0] before b[1]).
At each step, you take the front item from either Belt A or Belt B. The k-th item packed overall (1-indexed) receives a priority multiplier of k. So if an item with value v is packed at position k, it contributes v * k to the total score.
Find the maximum total score achievable by optimally choosing which belt to pick from at each step.
Note:
 * It is given that arrays are 1 indexed.
Input Format
The first line contains an integer, N, denoting the number of items on Belt A.
The next line contains an integer, M, denoting the number of items on Belt B.
Each line i of the N subsequent lines (where 1 <= i <= N) contains an integer describing A[i].
Each line i of the M subsequent lines (where 1 <= i <= M) contains an integer describing B[i].
Constraints
1 <= N <= 10^5
1 <= M <= 10^5
1 <= A[i] <= 10000
1 <= B[i] <= 10000
